li class="country" data-pos="3"><a href="http://theculturetrip.com/pacific/tahiti-french-polynesia/">Tahiti &amp; French Polynesia</a></li><li class="country" data-pos="4"><a href="http://theculturetrip.com/pacific/tokelau/">Tokelau</a></li><li class="country" data-pos="5"><a href="http://theculturetrip.com/pacific/tonga/">Tonga</a></li><li class="country" data-pos="6"><a href="http://theculturetrip.com/pacific/tuvalu/">Tuvalu</a></li><li class="country" data-pos="7"><a href="http://theculturetrip.com/pacific/vanuatu/">Vanuatu</a></li><li class="country" data-pos="8"><a href="http://theculturetrip.com/pacific/wallis-futuna/">Wallis &amp; Futuna</a></li></ul></div></div></li><li><a class="continent" href="http://theculturetrip.com/south-america/">South America</a><div class="dropdown south-america"><span class="indicator"><strong></strong></span><div class="dropdown-content"><ul data-cur="1"><li class="country" data-pos="1"><a href="http://theculturetrip.com/south-america/argentina/">Argentina</a></li><li class="country" data-pos="2"><a href="http://theculturetrip.com/south-america/bolivia/">Bolivia</a></li><li class="country" data-pos="3"><a href="http://theculturetrip.com/south-america/brazil/">Brazil</a></li><li class="country" data-pos="4"><a href="http://theculturetrip.com/south-america/chile/">Chile</a></li><li class="country" data-pos="5"><a href="http://theculturetrip.com/south-america/colombia/">Colombia</a></li><li class="country" data-pos="6"><a href="http://theculturetrip.com/south-america/ecuador/">Ecuador</a></li><li class="country" data-pos="7"><a href="http://theculturetrip.com/south-america/falkland-islands/">Falkland Islands</a></li><li class="country"><a href="/antarctica/">Antarctica</a></li></ul><ul data-cur="8"><li class="country" data-pos="1"><a href="http://theculturetrip.com/south-america/french-guiana/">French Guiana</a></li><li class="country" data-pos="2"><a href="http://theculturetrip.com/south-america/guyana/">Guyana</a></li><li class="country" data-pos="3"><a href="http://theculturetrip.com/south-america/paraguay/">Paraguay</a></li><li class="country" data-pos="4"><a href="http://theculturetrip.com/south-america/peru/">Peru</a></li><li class="country" data-pos="5"><a href="http://theculturetrip.com/south-america/suriname/">Suriname</a></li><li class="country" data-pos="6"><a href="http://theculturetrip.com/south-america/uruguay/">Uruguay</a></li><li class="country" data-pos="7"><a href="http://theculturetrip.com/south-america/venezuela/">Venezuela</a></li></ul></div></div></li></ul></div><div id="header-lower"><div class="wrapper"><div id="logo"><a title="Home" id="logo-link" href="http://theculturetrip.com"></a><h1 id="tagline">The best of art, food, culture and travel for every country</h1></div><div class="clear"></div></div></div><div id="header-scroll"><div class="wrapper"><img class="country-icon" src="http://icons.theculturetrip.com/country-icons/127.png"/><ul class="breadcrumb"><li><a href="http://theculturetrip.com">World</a></li><li><a href="http://theculturetrip.com/asia/">Asia</a></li><li><a href="http://theculturetrip.com/asia/japan/">Japan</a></li></ul><div class="search column"><form action="http://theculturetrip.com/search/" method="get"><input type="text" placeholder="Search..." class="search-text" name="q" value=""/><a href="#" class="clear-search">x</a></form></div></div></div></div>

			<ul id="share"><li><p class="text">Share</p></li><li><a title="Share on Facebook" href="http://www.facebook.com/share.php?u=http://theculturetrip.com/asia/japan/articles/kobe-s-top-10-must-try-restaurants-japanese-steakhouses" target="_blank" class="facebook"></a></li><li><a title="Share on Twitter" href="https://twitter.com/?status=Kobe%27s%20Top%2010%20Must-Try%20Restaurants%20 via @culturetrip http://theculturetrip.com/asia/japan/articles/kobe-s-top-10-must-try-restaurants-japanese-steakhouses" target="_blank" class="twitter"></a></li><li><a title="Share on Pinterest" href="//pinterest.com/pin/create/button/?url=http://theculturetrip.com/asia/japan/articles/kobe-s-top-10-must-try-restaurants-japanese-steakhouses&amp;description=Kobe%27s%20Top%2010%20Must-Try%20Restaurants%20" data-thumbnail="http://static.theculturetrip.com/images/56-266034-379166279-fe1c21dc3b-o.jpg" data-pin-do="buttonPin" data-pin-config="above" target="_blank" class="pinterest"></a></li><li><a title="Send via email" href="mailto:?&amp;subject=Kobe%27s%20Top%2010%20Must-Try%20Restaurants%20&amp;body=http://theculturetrip.com/asia/japan/articles/kobe-s-top-10-must-try-restaurants-japanese-steakhouses" class="newsletter"></a></li></ul>
			
			<div class="wrapper article">
			
				<div class="inner-wrapper ncms-sortables-boundary">
		
					<div id="content" class="column">

						<div class="panel">
						
							<div class="panel-content ncms-sortables-region ">					
	
								<div class="text-container"><h1></h1><h1><span style="font-weight: normal;">Kobe's Top 10 Must-Try Restaurants &amp; Japanese Steakhouses</span></h1><h2><span style="font-weight: normal;">Kobe has always been one of <a href="http://theculturetrip.com/asia/japan/">Japan</a>’s most cosmopolitan cities, from the 8th century when it was the country’s primary centre for trade with China, to its later role as one of the first ports in Japan to trade with the West. Kobe’s culinary scene reflects these international influences, yet Kobe is also no slouch when it comes to Japanese cuisine, with numerous restaurants cooking up the city’s biggest claim to fame: Kobe beef.</span></h2></div>
								
								
								<div class="imageWrapper inline-image imageFull"><figure><img src="http://static.theculturetrip.com/images/56-266029-379166279-fe1c21dc3b-o.jpg" alt="Japan"/><figcaption><em><a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/takahito/379166279/in/photolist-zvjVD-aP7uCM-9DvpcD-a7hzQk-6z5F3x-dCC3km-b3AzQD-b3ADjk-b3AtBT-b3Azt6-b3AAQZ-b3AAv2-b3ACZp-b3Avoe-b3AAcM-b3Ay9B-b3Atse-b3ADWi-b3AvYa-b3Ayu6-b3AEx6-b3ABaK-b3Auv6-b3AC4t-b3Axux-b3ACH8-b3AvGR-b3AwzP-b3Av64-e5hBf6-b3AyP8-b3AEf8-b3Az7x-ymX3-dAsFPr-6zoErq-3i2n2S-orSznF-6s9AaK-nLoCq9-cRE8RA-b3ACpV-b3AwPX-b3AwgP-b3Axa6-b3ADBZ-b3AuMk-b3ABtv-b3AtU6-b3ABLx" class="imageTextLink">© takahito/Flickr</a></em></figcaption></figure></div><div class="text-container"><h3><span style="font-weight: normal; text-decoration: underline;">Hyotan</span></h3>
<p>This no-frills eatery has
been packing in customers for more than 40 years with a single dish: <em>gyoza</em> (Japanese-style dumplings).
Hyotan’s dumplings are known for the light texture of their wrappers, which are
filled with savory cabbage, minced pork and leek. Tucked beneath the tracks of
Hanshin Sannomiya Station, Hyotan has no English sign, but look for the red <em>noren</em> curtains hanging in front of the
entrance. Particularly during the lunch hour rush, a meal at Hyotan offers an
interesting insight into Japanese food culture, with the city’s working class
cramming into the restaurant’s small interior to consume their <em>gyoza</em> at lightning speed. </p>
<p><i><a href="https://www.google.ca/maps/preview?gl=ca&amp;hq=Hyotan&amp;hnear=0x60007d812aed89d9:0xc7126106c2f670f4,Kobe,+Hyogo+Prefecture,+Japan&amp;daddr=1-31-37+Kitanagasadori,+Chuo+Ward,+Kobe,+Hyogo+Prefecture+650-0012&amp;panel=1&amp;f=d&amp;fb=1&amp;geocode=FTRUEQIdbOsOCCm1uA4R-o4AYDFIEtNJD">Hyotan,
1-31-37 Kitanagasadori, Chuo Ward, Kobe, Hyogo Prefecture, Japan</a></i><i>, +81 78
331 1354</i></p></div><div class="text-container"><h3><span style="text-decoration: underline; font-weight: normal;">Kitano Club</span></h3>
<p>Located on a hillside overlooking Kobe, <a href="http://www.kitanoclub.co.jp/">Kitano Club</a> is one of the city’s most popular fine-dining restaurants, known for its panoramic views and exceptional French cuisine. Open for more than 50 years, the restaurant’s menu changes monthly, with typical offerings including <em>foie gras</em>,<em> escargot</em>, and dishes featuring fresh fish, roast beef, duck or lamb with seasonal vegetables. The restaurant’s stylish interior is a unique spot for people-watching, filled with a mix of affluent locals and tourists. The separate bar and lounge area is a relaxing place to linger after dinner, offering views of Kobe in the valley below. </p>
<p><em><a href="https://www.google.ca/maps/preview?gl=ca&amp;hq=kitano+club+french+restaurant+kobe&amp;daddr=1-5-7+Kitanocho,+Chuo+Ward,+Kobe,+Hyogo+Prefecture+650-0002&amp;panel=1&amp;f=d&amp;fb=1&amp;geocode=FYGDEQIdIOEOCCmFYXGT3Y4AYDFlHhnPtJzVLg&amp;cid=3374775796166631013">Kitano Club, 1-5-7 Kitanocho, Chuo Ward, Kobe, Hyogo Prefecture, Japan</a>, +81 78 222 5123</em></p></div><div class="text-container"></div><div class="text-container"><h3><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Wakkoqu</span></h3><p>For many people, the name ‘Kobe’ is inextricably linked to its world-famous beef, and <a href="http://www.wakkoqu.com/english/index.html">Wakkoqu</a> is one of the best places in the city to try it. There are several set menus featuring various cuts of beef, which is then cooked directly in front of dinners on large iron griddles. The beef is served alongside side dishes like soup and fried vegetables, and the chefs provide guidance on which sauces and seasonings to add for different flavor experiences. The restaurant’s atmosphere is cosy and welcoming and English menus are available. </p>
<p><em><a href="https://www.google.ca/maps/preview?gl=ca&amp;hq=Wakkoqu&amp;hnear=0x60007d812aed89d9:0xc7126106c2f670f4,Kobe,+Hyogo+Prefecture,+Japan&amp;daddr=%E3%80%92650-0011+Hyogo+Prefecture,+Kobe,+Chuo+Ward,+Shimoyamatedori,+1%E2%88%9222%E2%88%9213,+%E3%83%92%E3%83%AB%E3%82%B5%25E">Wakkoqu, 1−22−13 Shimoyamatedori, Chuo Ward, Kobe, Hyogo Prefecture, Japan</a>, +81 78 222 0678</em></p></div><div class="imageWrapper inline-image imageFull"><figure><img src="http://static.theculturetrip.com/images/56-266032-kobewakkoqu.jpg" alt="Wakkoqu"/><figcaption><em><a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/chiszeo/4499178308/in/photolist-7Rwdgx-7Rztcd-7RwcYZ-7RzsUu-7RzsXN-7Rwd9T-7Rztj7-7RwcSD-7Rzt4u-7RwDPt-7Rwd3P-76fScu/" class="imageTextLink">© Chi (in Oz)/Flickr</a></em></figcaption></figure></div><div class="text-container"><h3><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Nishimura</span></h3><p>Opened in 1948, <a href="http://www.kobe-nishimura.jp/">Nishimura</a> is a timeless café that offers more than 20 different blends of coffee, all of which are roasted on-site. Set in a German-style house, this family-run café’s distinct half-timbered exterior has helped to establish it as a well-known Kobe landmark. The interior exudes the same elegant charm, decorated with antiques and beautiful wooden furniture. It was one of the first places in Japan to serve now-popular cappuccinos, Vienna coffees and coffee jelly, earning it a lasting place in Kobe’s coffee culture. Aside from coffee, the café offers a light menu of sandwiches, cakes, and other snacks. </p>
<p><em><a href="https://www.google.ca/maps/preview?ie=UTF-8&amp;gl=ca&amp;hq=Nishimura+Coffee&amp;hnear=0x60007d812aed89d9:0xc7126106c2f670f4,Kobe,+Hyogo+Prefecture,+Japan&amp;daddr=%E3%80%92650-0004+Hyogo+Prefecture,+Kobe,+Chuo+Ward,+Nakayamatedori,+%EF%BC%91%E4%B8%81%E7%9B%AE26%E2%88%259">Nishimura, 1-26-1 Nakayamate Dori, Kobe, Hyogo Prefecture, Japan</a>, +81 78-221-1872</em></p></div><div class="imageWrapper inline-image imageFull"><figure><img src="http://static.theculturetrip.com/images/56-266031-kobenishimura.jpg" alt="Nishimura"/><figcaption><em><a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/suzumenonamida/8583430917/in/photolist-8otDtj-e5uhRi-9ZiWue-9ZiWy2-9ZmQkE-9ZmZ6J-e5ujYe-7ugTNT-668pWn-24LxiT/" class="imageTextLink">© Manish Prabhune/Flickr</a></em></figcaption></figure></div><div class="text-container"><h3><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Totenkaku Royal Chinese Restaurant</span></h3>
<p>Totenkaku is set in the 19th century F.Bishop House, one of the oldest Western-style houses in the city. Open since 1945, this restaurant is well-known for its Peking duck, which is regularly flown in fresh from <a href="http://theculturetrip.com/asia/china/">China</a>. Aside from the famous duck, <a href="http://www.totenkaku.com/">Totenkaku</a> offers both a la carte and set menus of Chinese cuisine, including traditional floral teas that seem to bloom when served inside transparent pots. The interior lives up to the restaurant’s royal name, with high ceilings, deep red carpets, along with Chinese artifacts and artwork. </p>
<p><em><a href="https://www.google.ca/maps/preview?gl=ca&amp;hl=en&amp;daddr=3+Chome-14-18+Yamamotodori,+Chuo+Ward,+Kobe,+Hyogo+Prefecture+650-0003&amp;panel=1&amp;f=d&amp;fb=1&amp;geocode=Fe1tEQIdCMgOCCmzrlnQH48AYDFZ0EjCsDBFaQ&amp;cid=7585522683107397721">Totenkaku Royal Chinese Restaurant, 3 Chome-14-18 Yamamotodori, Chuo Ward, Kobe, Hyogo Prefecture, Japan</a>, +81 78 231 1351</em></p></div><div class="text-container"></div><div class="text-container"><h3><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Nailey’s Grill</span></h3><p>Nailey’s Grill is a friendly, European-style restaurant which is found nestled down a quiet alleyway. The international menu features burgers, sandwiches, soups, and Kobe beef, but the restaurant is particularly well-known for its Caesar salads. Supposedly, the restaurant’s chef traveled across the United States sampling Caesar salads and learning from each one, before returning to Japan to perfect the recipe. The staff speak both Japanese and English, and the interior is invitingly decorated with warm lighting, comfortable seating and muted pink walls. Jazz music adds to the laid-back atmosphere, making this spot a great place for a meal or even just post-dinner drinks. </p>
<p><em><a href="https://www.google.ca/maps/preview?ie=UTF-8&amp;fb=1&amp;gl=ca&amp;cid=11783519823374720751&amp;q=NAILEY%27S+GRILL&amp;ei=YqfYU9P8D8S1uASD-IH4CA&amp;ved=0CHcQ_BIwCg">Nailey’s Grill, 2-8-12 Kanocho, Chuo-ku, Kobe, Hyogo Prefecture, Japan</a>, +81 78 231 2008</em></p></div><div class="text-container"><h3><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Sun</span></h3><p><a href="http://www.dynac-japan.com/sun/shop_kobe.html">Sun</a> is one of the city’s few more avant-garde restaurants, known for its creative dishes and trendy decor. The dishes are typically prepared simply yet the addition of an unexpected ingredient or two keeps them imaginative. The menu features seasonal fish, grilled eel sushi, tofu, and premium meats such as Kagoshima pork. The restaurant is also known for its dim sum, which represents an innovative twist on the Chinese tradition. The contemporary interior features metallic mesh walls, earthenware pottery, dried flowers, and its 10th floor location allows for dramatic views of the Kobe cityscape. </p>
<p><em><a href="https://www.google.com/maps/preview?q=34.693329649299535,135.1939558982849&amp;source=newuser-ws">Sun, 1-10-1 Sannomiyacho Chuo-Ku, Kobe Kotsu Center Bldg. 10F, Kobe, Hyogo Prefecture, Japan</a>, +81 78 331 123</em></p></div><div class="text-container"></div><div class="text-container"><h3><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Café Freundlieb</span></h3><p>Set in the former Kobe Union Church, <a href="http://freundlieb.jp/">Café Freundlieb</a> offers one of the city’s most unusual dining atmospheres. The German owners were married in the church and later purchased the building to save it from demolition, subsequently making the decision to convert it into a café. The café’s design takes advantage of the church’s distinct architectural features, including its arched windows, exposed wooden beams and sky-high ceilings. The menu features salads, sandwiches, organic coffee, as well as fresh pastries, bread, cakes, and other desserts which are made at the on-site bakery. </p>
<p><em><a href="https://www.google.com/maps/preview?q=34.700632,135.195272">Café Freundlieb, 4–6–15 Ikuta-machi, Chūō-ku Kobe, Hyogo Prefecture, Japan</a>, +81 078-231-6051</em></p></div><div class="text-container"></div><div class="imageWrapper inline-image imageFull"><figure><img src="http://static.theculturetrip.com/images/56-266030-kobecafefreunlieb.jpg" alt="Cafe Freundlieb"/><figcaption><em><a href="http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Kobe_Union_Church09s5s3200.jpg" class="imageTextLink">© 663highland/Wikicommons</a></em></figcaption></figure></div><div class="text-container"><h3><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Steakland Kobe</span></h3><p><a href="http://steakland.jp/">Steakland Kobe</a> is a more affordable place to try Kobe beef that also offers English menus. The interior’s dark wood paneling is reminiscent of an American steakhouse, yet the arrangement of tables around the central griddle distinguishes it as a <em>teppanyaki</em> restaurant. The set menus feature steak, miso soup, rice, Japanese pickles, dipping sauces, salad, and grilled vegetables, plus coffee or orange juice at the end of the meal. Keep in mind that the cheapest steak sets offered are actually regular beef, and not the legendary Kobe beef. </p>
<p><em><a href="https://www.google.ca/maps/preview?ie=UTF-8&amp;gl=ca&amp;hq=Steakland+Kobe&amp;hnear=Steakland+Kobe&amp;daddr=%E3%80%92650-0021+Hyogo+Prefecture,+Kobe,+Chuo+Ward,+Kitanagasadori,+1%E2%88%928%E2%88%922,+%E5%AE%AE%E8%BF%BD%E3%83%93%E3%83%AB+1F%E3%83%BB2F&amp;panel=1&amp;f=d&amp;fb=1&amp;g">Steakland Kobe, 1-8-2 Kitanagasadori, Chuo-ku | Miyasako Bldg. 1-2F, Kobe, Hyogo Prefecture, Japan</a>, +81 78-332-1653</em></p></div><div class="video panel"><div class="panel-content"><iframe title="YouTube video player" class="youtube-player video-player" type="text/html" width="667.98614501953" height="376" frameborder="0" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/f5iobrn0UdI?wmode=opaque"></iframe></div></div><div class="text-container"><h3><u style="font-weight: normal;">Bistrot Café de Paris 
</u></h3><p><a href="http://www.cafe-de-paris.jp/">Bistrot Café de Paris</a> offers authentic French cuisine and one of the city’s few outdoor dining areas. The menu features soups, sandwiches, salads, pizzas, as well as classic French dishes like beef bourguignon and <em>crème brûlée</em>, in addition to an excellent selection of Belgian beers and wine. A popular gathering place for locals, tourists and expats, the chefs are French and the staff speak English, French and Japanese. The interior is decorated to resemble a typical French café, complete with a live accordion player serenading dinners on certain days. </p>
<p><em><a href="https://www.google.ca/maps/preview?ie=UTF-8&amp;gl=ca&amp;hq=Bistrot+Caf%C3%A9+de+Paris&amp;daddr=1+Chome-7-21+Yamamotodori,+Chuo+Ward,+Kobe,+Hyogo+Prefecture&amp;panel=1&amp;f=d&amp;fb=1&amp;geocode=FeN3EQIdkNkOCCmLRDnG4I4AYDFR-JoEZgOzjw&amp;cid=10354623704953714769">Bistrot Café de Paris, 1 Chome-7-21 Yamamotodori, Chuo Ward, Kobe, Hyogo Prefecture, Japan</a>, +81 78 241 9448</em></p></div><div class="text-container"><p><em><br/></em></p>
<p><em>By Jessica Dawdy</em></p>
<p><em><br/></em></p></div><div class="clear"></div>
								
							</div>
							
